{"title_page": "Magno Mocelin", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Magno\n| image = \n| fullname = Magno Mocelin\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|2|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Curitiba]], Brazil\n| height = 1.74 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1994 | clubs1 = [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]] | caps1 = 21 | goals1 = 5\n| years2 = 1995\u20131996 | clubs2 = [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]] | caps2 = 13 | goals2 = 0\n| years4 = 1996\u20131998 | clubs4 = [[FC Groningen|Groningen]] | caps4 = 48 | goals4 = 19\n| years5 = 1998\u20132004 | clubs5 = [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]] | caps5 = 181 | goals5 = 22\n| years6 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs6 = [[De Graafschap]] | caps6 = 22 | goals6 = 4\n| years7 = 2005\u20132008 | clubs7 = [[AC Omonia|Omonia]] | caps7 = 58 | goals7 = 17\n| years8 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs8 = [[AEK Larnaca FC|AEK Larnaca]] | caps8 = 25 | goals8 = 1\n| totalcaps = 368 | totalgoals = 68\n}}\n\n'''Magno Mocelin''' (born 26 February 1974), known as '''Magno''', is a  Brazilian former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\nHis 15-year professional career, which was spent in four countries, was mainly associated with [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]] in Spain, for which he appeared in 208 official games and played in one [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] final.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Curitiba]], [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]], Magno started playing professionally with [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo]] and [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense]]. He moved overseas in 1996, spending three seasons with Dutch [[Eredivisie]] club [[FC Groningen]] and [[1997\u201398 Eredivisie|being relegated at the end of his last]].\n\nAged 24, Magno joined [[La Liga]] side [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]] for the [[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u201399 campaign]], remaining six years with the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basques]] and playing an important attacking role (mainly as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] as the team [[2000\u201301 UEFA Cup|reached the 2001]] [[2001 UEFA Cup Final|final]] of the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] which was lost to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]], where he was [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://servicios.elcorreo.com/especiales/alaves05/los_mas_nombrados.html|title=Los m\u00e1s albiazules|trans-title=The most white-and-blue|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|language=Spanish|date=2005|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2000/matches/round=1532/match=67741/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Liverpool win nine-goal epic with golden goal|publisher=UEFA|date=1 September 2014|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref> He subsequently returned to the Netherlands, signing for [[De Graafschap]].\n\nAfter a season back in the [[Netherlands]] with [[De Graafschap]] \u2013 also [[2004\u201305 Eredivisie|relegated from the top level]] \u2013 Magno started a [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] adventure in 2005, first playing with [[AC Omonia]]. On 6 June 2008, he moved to fellow [[Cypriot First Division|First Division]] side [[AEK Larnaca FC]] on a one-year contract.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1821}}\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|6958}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magno Mocelin}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A players]]\n[[Category:Clube de Regatas do Flamengo footballers]]\n[[Category:Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:FC Groningen players]]\n[[Category:De Graafschap players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:Cypriot First Division players]]\n[[Category:AC Omonia players]]\n[[Category:AEK Larnaca FC players]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Cyprus]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Magno\n| image = \n| fullname = Magno Mocelin\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|2|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Curitiba]], Brazil\n| height = 1.74 m\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = \n| clubnumber = \n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 1994 | clubs1 = [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]] | caps1 = 21 | goals1 = 5\n| years2 = 1995\u20131996 | clubs2 = [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]] | caps2 = 13 | goals2 = 0\n| years4 = 1996\u20131998 | clubs4 = [[FC Groningen|Groningen]] | caps4 = 48 | goals4 = 19\n| years5 = 1998\u20132004 | clubs5 = [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]] | caps5 = 181 | goals5 = 22\n| years6 = 2004\u20132005 | clubs6 = [[De Graafschap]] | caps6 = 22 | goals6 = 4\n| years7 = 2005\u20132008 | clubs7 = [[AC Omonia|Omonia]] | caps7 = 58 | goals7 = 17\n| years8 = 2008\u20132009 | clubs8 = [[AEK Larnaca FC|AEK Larnaca]] | caps8 = 25 | goals8 = 1\n| totalcaps = 368 | totalgoals = 68\n| club-update = \n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Magno Mocelin''' (born 26 February 1974), known as '''Magno''', is a  [[Brazil]]ian retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\nHis 15-year professional career, which was spent in four countries, was mainly associated with [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s|Alav\u00e9s]] in Spain, for which he appeared in 208 official games and played in one [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] final.\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Curitiba]], [[Paran\u00e1 (state)|Paran\u00e1]], Magno started playing professionally with [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo]] and [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense]]. He moved overseas in 1996, spending three seasons with Dutch [[Eredivisie]] club [[FC Groningen]] and [[1997\u201398 Eredivisie|being relegated at the end of his last]].\n\nAged 24, Magno joined [[La Liga]] side [[Deportivo Alav\u00e9s]] for the [[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u201399 campaign]], remaining six years with the [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basques]] and playing an important attacking role (mainly as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] as the team [[2000\u201301 UEFA Cup|reached the 2001]] [[2001 UEFA Cup Final|final]] of the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] which was lost to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]], where he was [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://servicios.elcorreo.com/especiales/alaves05/los_mas_nombrados.html|title=Los m\u00e1s albiazules|trans-title=The most white-and-blue|newspaper=[[El Correo]]|language=Spanish|date=2005|accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2000/matches/round=1532/match=67741/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Liverpool win nine-goal epic with golden goal|publisher=UEFA|date=1 September 2014|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref> He subsequently returned to the Netherlands, signing for [[De Graafschap]].\n\nAfter a season back in the [[Netherlands]] with [[De Graafschap]] \u2013 also [[2004\u201305 Eredivisie|relegated from the top level]] \u2013 Magno started a [[Cyprus|Cypriot]] adventure in 2005, first playing with [[AC Omonia]]. On 6 June 2008, he moved to fellow [[Cypriot First Division|First Division]] side [[AEK Larnaca FC]] on a one-year contract.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|1821}}\n*{{FootballDatabase.eu|6958}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magno Mocelin}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A players]]\n[[Category:Clube de Regatas do Flamengo footballers]]\n[[Category:Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:FC Groningen players]]\n[[Category:De Graafschap players]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo Alav\u00e9s players]]\n[[Category:Cypriot First Division players]]\n[[Category:AC Omonia players]]\n[[Category:AEK Larnaca FC players]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Cyprus]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magno_Mocelin"}
